[00:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hi. Welcome to another video. So, remember my video on the Ralph loop? That plugin where you trap Claude code in a loop until it actually finishes the job?'

[00:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, Michael took that concept and basically put it on steroids. It\'s called Ralphy, and it\'s a completely different beast. See, the original Ralph was clever. It used Claude code\'s hooks API to'

[00:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'intercept the exit and force the AI back into the task until it outputs a completion promise. Simple, effective, but limited.'

[00:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ralphy is not a plugin. It\'s a full orchestration system. Think of it like this. Ralph was a leash for one dog. Ralphy is a pack manager for multiple AI dogs that can run in parallel across'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different branches, pulling tasks from PRDs, YAML files, or even your GitHub issues. Let me show you what this thing can do. So, the core idea is similar.'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You have tasks. You want an AI to complete them. You don\'t want to babysit. But Ralphy scales this up in a very smart way. First, it supports multiple AI engines.'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You\'re not locked into Claude code anymore. You can use open code, code XC I, or even cursor\'s agent mode. So, if you have a preference or if one'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model is cheaper for your use case, you can swap engines with a single flag. For example, if I want to use open code instead of Claude, I just run Ralphy.sh - open code.'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That\'s it. Same loop, different brain. Now, here\'s where it gets interesting. The killer feature is parallel execution.'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In my original Ralph video, the loop ran one task at a time. If you had 10 things to build, Claude would do them sequentially. That\'s fine for small projects, but if you\'re building something'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'serious, that\'s slow. Ralphy can spin up multiple agents simultaneously. Each agent gets its own isolated Git work tree. That means they\'re not stepping on each'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other\'s files. Agent one can be building the auth system while agent two is writing the database schema, and agent three is setting up the tests. All at the same time.'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You control the concurrency with the dash-dash-max-dash-parallel flag. So, if I run Ralphy.sh-dash-parallel-dash-dash-max-dash-parallel-5, I get five AI agents working in'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parallel, which is kind of awesome. Now, let\'s talk about task sources, because this is where Ralphy really shines. With the original Ralph, you had to write your prompt directly in'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the command. It was a single task, single loop. Ralphy accepts entire task lists. You can give it a PRD file, which is just a markdown file with checkbox style'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tasks. Ralphy reads that file, parses each unchecked item, and sends them to the AI agents one by one. As [clears throat] each task completes, it marks the checkbox.'

[03:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, you get a real-time view of progress just by looking at your PRD. But it gets better. If you use YAML files instead, you can define parallel groups. So, you can say'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these three tasks can run at the same time, but this fourth task depends on them, so wait until they\'re done. That\'s actual dependency management for AI tasks, which is pretty cool for sure.'

[03:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you\'re a GitHub person, Ralphy can pull tasks directly from your GitHub issues. You can even filter by labels. So, if you label your issues as AI task, Ralphy will only pick up those.'

[04:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When an AI completes the issue, it auto closes it. Your project management and AI automation are now the same thing. Now, let\'s talk about the Git workflow,'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because this is where a lot of AI tools fall apart. When you have multiple agents, you need branch management. Otherwise, they\'re all committing to the same branch and creating merge conflicts'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constantly. Ralphy handles this with the dash-dash-branch-dash-per-dash-task flag. Each task gets its own feature branch. The AI works on that branch, makes'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'commits, and when it\'s done, Ralphy can automatically create a pull request with dash-dash-create-dash-PR. You can even make them draft PRs if you want to review before merging.'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here\'s the really clever part. Ralphy has built-in merge conflict resolution. If agents finish at different times and their branches conflict, Ralphy can use the AI itself to resolve'

[05:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the conflicts. It\'s AI all the way down. So, let me show you this in action. I have a YAML file here with five tasks. Three of them are in parallel group one,'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'meaning they can run simultaneously. Two are in parallel group two, meaning they wait for group one to finish. I run Ralphy.sh, watch the terminal. You\'ll see three spinners pop up.'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Each one shows which task that agent is working on, how long it\'s been running, and the current step. It\'s like watching a little army of coders. Agent one finishes first.'

[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It creates a PR. Now, the group two tasks start. They run on top of the merged code from group one. This is what I mean by orchestration. You\'re not managing individual AI'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sessions anymore. You\'re managing a workflow. Now, let\'s talk about when to use this versus the original Ralph. If you have a single, complex task with clear success criteria,'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like build this app and make all tests pass, the original Ralph is simpler and more direct. You don\'t need the overhead of Ralphy. But if you have a list of tasks,'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you want parallelization, if you\'re working with a team and need proper branch management, Ralphy is the way to go. I\'ve been using Ralphy for refactoring projects.'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll create a YAML file with all the modules I want to migrate, set them to run in parallel, and let it chew through the work overnight. In the morning, I have five pull'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'requests waiting for review. Each one is isolated, tested, and ready to merge. The cost tracking is also nice. Ralphy shows you estimated costs per'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'task, so you can see exactly where your API credits are going. For Claude code, it shows estimated costs. For open code, it shows actual costs. For cursor, it tracks API duration since'

[07:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'their pricing is different. One thing to keep in mind, the more parallel agents you run, the more resources you\'re using. Git work trees aren\'t free in terms of'

[07:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disk space. And if you\'re using a rate-limited API, you might hit throttling. So, start conservative with dash-dash-max-dash-parallel-3, and scale up once you know your setup'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can handle it. Also, your task definitions matter a lot. Each task needs to be self-contained. If task A depends on code that task B creates,'

[07:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you need to put them in different parallel groups. Otherwise, you\'ll get failures because the code doesn\'t exist yet. But if you structure your tasks well, Ralphy is basically an autonomous development team.'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You become the project manager. You define what needs to be done, and the AI figures out how to do it. This is pretty amazing, to be honest. It\'s taking the concept of AI-assisted'

[08:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coding and turning it into AI-managed coding. You\'re not pair programming anymore. You\'re delegating. I have been using Ralph loops here and there, but I\'m still deviating towards using'

[08:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Veridian for most of my stuff with sub agents and everything, as it\'s super graphical for me to manage different tasks. I just make in sub agents here, and ask it to like keep going until a'

[08:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'task is fully finished, and keep tabs on the main agent\'s work, which is pretty cool for sure. Overall, it\'s pretty cool. Anyway, share your thoughts below and subscribe to the'

[09:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'channel. You can also [music] donate via super thanks option or join the channel as well and get some perks. I\'ll see you in the next [music] video. Bye.'
